  abstract  = {Alzheimer’s disease (AD) is the most common type of dementia, affecting at least 27 million people and corresponding to 60–70% of all dementia cases. The disease typically manifests through a progressive loss of episodic memory and cognitive function, subsequently causing language and visuospatial skills deficiencies, often accompanied by behavioral disorders such as apathy, aggressiveness, and depression. From an anatomopathological perspective, AD is characterized by two prototypical lesions: senile plaques composed of β-amyloid protein accumulation (Aβ42) and neurofibrillary tangles composed of phosphorylated tau protein (P-tau).}
}


